{
  "text": "Several studies have emphasized that it is important to control the properties of the perturbation. Diener et al. [CITATION_1] as well as Runge et al. [CITATION_2] showed that the kinematic parameters of the perturbation have a significant influence on the body's linked-segment kinetics and neuromuscular (EMG) response. Others have found that a typical ramp displacement profile used in surface perturbations actually produces two separate perturbations (initial acceleration and subsequent deceleration), each of which affects the elicited postural response [CITATION_3] . Finally, it has been shown that the postural response after perturbation is greatly affected by the direction of perturbation [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "43288220",
